Nope.

What we&#39;ve danced around without discussing in this thread, is Code on
Demand.  If you want a batch of operations to succeed or fail as a unit
(presumably what everyone but me means by atomic), then you may well
have a compelling reason to implement REST&#39;s optional constraint.

An applet running in the client could GET each member of the set, cache
it, DELETE it, and if any deletion fails, PUT each member back.  Or
somesuch.  All the benefit of a uniform interface, while implementing
an operation that otherwise just doesn&#39;t fit with REST.

-Eric
